ard.","error_type":null,"evidence_refs":["TR_Dynamics+22+Batteries:C005","TR_Dynamics+22+Batteries:C001"]},{"option_id":"D","label":"Incorrect","justification":"Evidence shows NFPP has good stability but does not support a universal guarantee against thermal runaway under all abuse conditions.","error_type":"boundary_overreach","evidence_refs":["TR_Dynamics+22+Batteries:C014","TR_Dynamics+22+Batteries:C017"]},{"option_id":"E","label":"Correct","justification":"NFM peaks at 148 °C, NFPP main peak at 436.6 °C; difference is ~288 °C, supporting substantially earlier thermal event for NFM.","error_type":null,"evidence_refs":["TR_Dynamics+22+Batteries:C005","TR_Dynamics+22+Batteries:C001"]},{"option_id":"F","label":"Incorrect","justification":"Full-cell ARC behavior depends on multiple components; activation energy alone is insufficient to determine system-level thermal runaway severity.","error_type":"causal_overclaim","evidence_refs":["TR_Dynamics+22+Batteries:C015","TR_Dynamics+22+Batteries:C016"]}]},"analysis":{"target_cognitive_object":"Comparative thermal hazard assessment between NFPP and NFM cathodes using activation energy, heat generation, and peak temperature","primary_boundary":"Component-level DSC data; cannot universally guarantee full-cell behavior","intended_error_modes":["trend_reversal","boundary_overreach","causal_overclaim"],"disallowed_extrapolations":["Activation energy alone determines full-cell thermal runaway","NFPP immunity to thermal runaway under all conditions"]}},{"qid":"Q2","type":"MCQ","solver_view":{"stem":"DSC measurements on a hard carbon (HC) anode at three SOC levels (20%, 60%, 100%) show total heat releases of 346.8, 582.6, and 844.2 J g⁻¹ respectively. At 60% SOC, a prominent exothermic peak appears at 57 °C absent in the other two SOC samples, attributed to reactive sodium intermediates and SEI maturation. When the anode is over-sodiated beyond 100% SOC, total heat release increases ~70% but exothermic reaction temperature does not